==============================================================================
🔐 DATA SAFETY
==============================================================================
WHY THIS SCRIPT IS HIGH RISK
--------------------------------
- This action combines private delivery credentials with detailed community analytics. A single shared script or export can expose both the streamer’s contact information and information about viewers.
- The gateway address commonly contains the streamer’s real phone number. Publishing it can invite spam, harassment, stalking, or attempts to misuse the number for account recovery.
- The sender email can be targeted for phishing, impersonation, credential-stuffing, and password-reset attacks.
- An exposed app password may allow someone else to send mail through the account and can remain valid independently of the normal account password.
- Saved reports contain viewer usernames, attendance history, subscription activity, follows, raids, bits, top-chatter information, and engagement metrics. Publishing them can expose viewer behavior without their knowledge.

NEVER SHARE THESE ITEMS
--------------------------------
- Never publish a completed .cs file, Streamer.bot export, screenshot, log, repository, Discord attachment, Pastebin entry, or support ticket containing a real gateway, phone number, email address, or app password.
- Never livestream or record the credential lines, SMTP configuration, generated report contents, or local report folder when real information is visible.
- Never use the email account’s normal sign-in password in this script. Use only a revocable app-specific password when supported.
- Do not publicly post generated stream summaries unless viewer identifiers and private support details have been intentionally removed and sharing is appropriate for the community.
- Do not assume deleting a post makes the information private again. Public files may be mirrored, cached, indexed, downloaded, or preserved in repository history.

BEFORE SHARING OR SELLING THIS TEMPLATE
--------------------------------
- Replace the destination with YOUR_PHONE_NUMBER@YOUR_CARRIER_GATEWAY.
- Replace every sender address with YOUR_EMAIL@example.com and every app password with YOUR_APP_PASSWORD.
- Search the complete script, decoded export, import file, ZIP archive, screenshots, and README for @, smtp, password, credential, phone-number patterns, Windows user-folder paths, drive-letter paths, and real channel identities.
- Inspect the final packaged files themselves. An old credential can remain inside a decoded JSON file, import export, backup script, archive, or copied action even when the visible .cs file is clean.
- Remove or anonymize sample reports and logs because they can contain viewer names, attendance records, support activity, timestamps, and other community data.
- Verify that the public version uses placeholders before uploading it to Ko-fi, GitHub, Discord, cloud storage, or any marketplace.

PROTECTING GENERATED REPORTS
--------------------------------
- The StreamSummaries folder is ordinary local storage and is not automatically encrypted. Anyone with access to the computer, synced cloud folder, backup, or shared Windows profile may be able to read the reports.
- Store reports only as long as needed, restrict access to the folder, and avoid placing it inside a publicly shared or automatically published directory.
- Review reports before sending them to another person. Remove viewer names and support details that are not necessary for the recipient.
- Consider whether collecting and retaining attendance and support histories matches the privacy expectations of the channel and the laws or platform rules that apply to you.

SAFER CONFIGURATION PRACTICES
--------------------------------
- Move SMTP credentials into protected Streamer.bot variables, environment variables, or a dedicated secret manager instead of hardcoding them when possible.
- Use a separate sending account with minimal privileges, enable multi-factor authentication, and create a unique app password used only by this automation.
- Set SendSmsEnabled to false in public demonstrations and test the report-generation path without live credentials.
- Keep diagnostic logs private and avoid logging the full SMTP credential object, destination address, generated message body, or complete report content.

IF INFORMATION IS ACCIDENTALLY EXPOSED
--------------------------------
- Immediately revoke the exposed app password and create a replacement only after all public and shared copies have been sanitized.
- If the normal email password was ever used, change it immediately, sign out other sessions, review recent activity, and confirm multi-factor authentication is active.
- Delete or replace every exposed copy, including message attachments, repository commits and history, releases, mirrors, cloud shares, and downloadable ZIP archives.
- Treat an exposed gateway as an exposed phone number. Monitor for spam or harassment, block abusive contacts, and contact the carrier when necessary.
- If viewer reports were exposed, remove access promptly, identify what data was included, notify affected people when appropriate, and stop further syncing or distribution.
- Assume the information may already have been copied. Credential rotation and access review are required; deletion alone is not a complete response.

